SSH — the secure shell.

SSH, the secure shell, is how you log in to a remote Linux machine and run commands on it as if you were sitting at its console. It encrypts absolutely everything, it authenticates both ends, and it is the universal administration protocol; you use it the exact same way on every Linux box, every cloud provider, and every container. There are two ends to it: the ssh client, the ssh command you run on your own machine, and the sshd server, a daemon running on the remote machine, listening on TCP port twenty-two by default.

Basic usage is just ssh, then user-at-host. Add dash-lowercase-p and a number for a custom port, and note that's lowercase p for the client. Dash-i lets you point at a specific key file. And you can tack a command in quotes on the end to run just that one command remotely and exit, which is great for scripting.

Now, the part that trips up newcomers: host key verification. The very first time you connect to a host, SSH shows you that host's fingerprint, something like an ED25519 fingerprint, SHA256, then a string, and it asks, "are you sure you want to continue connecting?" This is your protection against a man-in-the-middle attack, someone impersonating the server. So on that first connection, you should verify the fingerprint out-of-band: ask the administrator, or check the cloud provider's console. Once you accept it, the key is stored in your known-hosts file and checked silently on every future connection.

And that leads to a warning you must never ignore. If you ever connect and see, in big alarming letters, "warning: remote host identification has changed," it means the host's key is different from the one you stored. Now, most of the time that's innocent, the server was reinstalled or moved to a new IP address. But it can also mean an attack. So do not blindly accept it. Either verify the new key out-of-band, or, once you've genuinely confirmed the change is legitimate, remove the stale entry with ssh-keygen dash-capital-R and the hostname, and reconnect.
